results.notes:
Fruiting bodies were a dull yellowish brown colour with a light pink tinge. Spores were globose, spiny, 7-9 um diameter. Basidia 4-sterigmate.

As far as I can tell there are only 3 Hydnangium species described from Australia.

Hydnangium carneum
Hydnangium archeri
Hydnangium sublamellatum

The first two species have larger spores and bi-sterigmate basidia.

The spores and basidia of this specimen seem to match the description of Hydnangium sublamellatum, however the macro-morphology doesn’t fit that species so well. H. sublamellatum is described as having a sublamellate to lamellate hymenium and a small stipe, whereas this specimen had a loculate hymenium and minimal stipe (if any). There were only faint remnants of a columnella.

Um basidioma completamente roxo
incrustações amilóides nos cistídios

results.notes:
Cosmopolitan, in an avenue with old oak trees, growing on groups, close to or on people’s yards.
Cap 4-6 cms, brown to yellow/brown, centrally depressed with a darker center, no reddish-brown areas, viscid, with margins striate-tuberculate, peeling ½ of the radius, margin upturned with age. Gills cream, notched, and crowded, some forking. Stipe white, clavate, hollow in all cases (4-6) x (1-2). Taste peppery, smell not strong, perhaps a little like bleach.
Spore color pale to medium cream, Romagnesi 2a to 2c; spores (7.0 – 8.2) x (5.5 – 6.8) Q aver= 1.26, broadly ellipsoid; Woo 2b-2c, with warts .5 to .8 long, some partially connected and, warts and hilar patch little amyloid, or not at all. Cheilocystidia ampullate about 40 × 10. Pileopellis with interwoven hyphal cells, 3-4 microns wide, multiseptated, articulated, some branched, with ends tapering to a point or a little clavate with round ends.
While the microscopy is very similar within species in this group, I believe that the cheilocystidia and the epicutal hyhal ends closely resemble most those on Roberts fig 22, for Russula cerolens. I am drying some material for future sequencing use.

results.notes:
Specimen A:
Growing near wet area dominated by hemlock and white pine, some hardwoods present.
Cuticle peels nearly 100% of radius.
Taste acrid.
Spores 8-9.5 × 7-7.5, warts up to around 0.8 micron with scattered short connections.

Specimen B:
Growing on the edge of oak-dominated woods near the border of a wet area dominated by hemlock and white pine.
Cuticle peels around 70% of radius.
Taste acrid.
Spores 7.5-9.5 × 7-8.5, warts exceeding 1.5 microns in height with few connections/angles.

Specimens A and B found growing around 20 yards apart, with similar appearance, taste, and spore dimensions. But, likely different species based upon the heights of the warts on the spores. The Kibby/Fatto key did not lead to any good matches.
Note that the spore photos were cropped differently, which causes the spores to seem quite differently sized (at a glance).
